 may even possess consciousness.Taking readers deep into the sensory world of bees, Chittka illustrates how bee brains are unparalleled in the animal kingdom in terms of how much sophisticated material is packed into their tiny nervous systems. He looks at their innate behaviors and the ways their evolution as foragers may have contributed to their keen spatial memory. Chittka also examines the psychological differences between bees and the ethical dilemmas that arise in conservation and laboratory settings because bees feel and think. Throughout, he touches on the fascinating history behind the study of bee behavior.Exploring an insect whose sensory experiences rival those of humans, The Mind of a Bee reveals the singular abilities of some of the world’s most incredible creatures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aBeesxBehavior. 0aBeesxPsychology. 7aNATURE / Animals / Insects & Spiders.2bisacsh  aAdvertising.  aAlcoholic beverage.  aAnalogy.  aApis cerana.  aBearing (navigation).  aBee.  aBeehive.  aBeekeeper.  aBeekeeping.  aBeeswax.  aBiological neural network.  aBombus terrestris.  aBrood (honey bee).  aBumblebee.  aCarpenter bee.  aCharles Darwin.  aChemical substance.  aCollective intelligence.  aComputation.  aComputer scientist.  aConsciousness.  aCounting.  aDarwinism.  aDecision-making.  aDesk.  aDetection.  aEarthworm.  aEntomology.  aEventuality (phrenology).  aForaging.  aFungus.  aGestapo.  aHoney bee.  aIdentifier.  aIllustration.  aInformation sharing.  aInner ear.  aInsect.  aInsecticide.  aInstant.  aInvertebrate.  aIridescence.  aKarl von Frisch.  aLarva.  aLearning.  aLens (optics).  aMachine learning.  aMammary gland.  aMason bee.  aMechanoreceptor.  aMicrovillus.  aMotley crew.  aMotor lea